We should also consider binary cmdlets. One option is to accept a type that implements an interface, something like:

```c#
public interface IValidateSetGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<string> Get();
}
public class MyValidateSetGenerator : IValidateSetGenerator
{
    public IEnumerable<string> Get()
    {
        yield return "Something";
    }
}
...
    [Parameter()]
    [ValidateSet(typeof(MyValidateSetGenerator)]
    public string Something { get; set; }
```

This could probably work in PowerShell too (the interface would be defined in System.Management.Automation.dll.

I think we'd need a way of passing `$PSBoundParameters` to truly cover most of the scenarios where people are resorting to dynamic parameters today.

@powercode IntelliSense can call attributes very often. ValidateSet with script block becomes similar to ValidateScript (can run unpredictably long).


Perhaps we should do only IValidateSetGenerator (not script block) because we want support interfaces in PowerShell classes.

Also could we add IValidateSetGenerator not only in ValidateSet attribute: ValidateScript, ValidatePattern, ... for IntelliSense support?

@iSazonov I don't think that would be much of a problem. Most people know not to have long-running commands in intellisense code. People are already working around this issue using the less-friendly dynamicparam block and passing a ValidateSetAttribute to the attribute collection.

I feel the problem with using an interface for this is that a lot of PowerShell coders aren't programmers. It's one thing to support classes, it's another thing to force the user to use them. Just my opinion ofc. The 'PowerShell way' here is to support a ScriptBlock.

@lzybkr would the following not be easier:
```c#
public interface IValidateSetGenerator
{
    IEnumerable<string> Get();
}
public class MyValidateSetGenerator : IValidateSetGenerator
{
    public IEnumerable<string> Get()
    {
        yield return "Something";
    }
}

[Parameter()]
[ValidateSet(MyValidateSetGenerator)]
public string Something { get; set; }
```

and just have a ValidateSet overload that takes in an IValidateSetGenerator, rather than using typeof?
